<h2>Review Generation and Solicitation Statistics</h2>
<p>How and when businesses ask for reviews impacts the volume and quality they receive.</p>
<p><strong>40. 40% of consumers are most likely to respond to email review requests.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey-2025/">BrightLocal</a>, 2025)
Email outperforms SMS, in-person requests, and social media for review solicitation. This number grew from 32% in 2024.</p>
<p><strong>41. 27% of consumers respond when asked for a review in person.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey-2025/">BrightLocal</a>, 2025)
In-person requests remain effective, especially for service businesses like dentists, salons, and <a href="/blog/home-services-seo-guide/">home service providers</a>.</p>
<p><strong>42. 29% of consumers wrote a business review in the past year.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey-2025/">BrightLocal</a>, 2025)
Up from 27% the year before. The gap between review readers (95%) and review writers (29%) is enormous.</p>
<p><strong>43. 75% of consumers leave reviews to help businesses improve.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey-2025/">BrightLocal</a>, 2025)
Most reviewers have good intentions. Only 7% leave reviews primarily after negative experiences.</p>
<p><strong>44. 96% of consumers are open to writing a review when asked.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey-2025/">BrightLocal</a>, 2025)
The barrier is not willingness. It is the ask. Businesses that <a href="/blog/get-more-google-reviews-local-business/">ask customers for reviews</a> consistently outperform those that wait.</p>
<p><strong>45. 23% of consumers say their experience was not noteworthy enough to review.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/local-consumer-review-survey-2025/">BrightLocal</a>, 2025)
Framing the ask around specific outcomes ("How was your cleaning today?") overcomes this objection.</p>
<h2>Industry-Specific Review Statistics</h2>
<p>Review patterns vary significantly across industries.</p>
<p><strong>46. 86% of job seekers research company reviews before applying.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.glassdoor.com/">Glassdoor</a>, 2025)
Reviews do not just affect customers. They affect hiring. Employer brand depends on review quality.</p>
<p><strong>47. 52% of travelers avoid hotels without any reviews.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.demandsage.com/online-review-statistics/">DemandSage</a>, 2025)
Hospitality businesses face the steepest penalty for zero reviews.</p>
<p><strong>48. The average review length dropped from 600 words in 2010 to 200 words today.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.brightlocal.com/research/consumer-reviews-historical-trends/">BrightLocal</a>, 2025)
Reviews are getting shorter. Mobile usage drives this shift.</p>
<p><strong>49. 84% of Amazon sellers consider reviews extremely critical to their business.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.ecomengine.com/">eComEngine</a>, 2025)
For ecommerce, reviews are the primary trust signal above product descriptions and brand reputation.</p>
<p><strong>50. TripAdvisor reviews are 3x longer than reviews on other platforms.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com/">TripAdvisor</a>, 2025)
Travel reviews tend to be detailed. The average hotel review on TripAdvisor runs 688 characters.</p>
