<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<p><strong>What is the most important online review statistic in 2026?</strong></p>
<p>95% of consumers read reviews before purchasing. This single number proves that reviews are not a "nice to have." They are a requirement for every business that sells to consumers. Combine this with the fact that <a href="/blog/google-reviews-statistics/">Google holds 73% of review volume</a>, and the priority becomes clear.</p>
<p><strong>How many reviews does a business need to be credible?</strong></p>
<p>The minimum threshold is 5 reviews, which increases conversions by 270% according to the Spiegel Research Center. For maximum credibility, aim for 100+ reviews. 43% of consumers prefer businesses with more than 100 reviews. Consistent <a href="/blog/get-more-google-reviews-local-business/">review generation</a> matters more than occasional spikes.</p>
<p><strong>Do review responses actually impact revenue?</strong></p>
<p>Yes. Businesses that respond to at least 25% of their reviews earn 35% more revenue than those that do not respond. 63% of consumers expect a response within 1 week. Ignoring reviews signals that a business does not care about customer feedback.</p>
<p><strong>What percentage of online reviews are fake?</strong></p>
<p>An estimated 30% of all online reviews are fake. Google removed 240 million policy-violating reviews in 2024 alone. The <a href="https://www.ftc.gov/business-guidance/blog/2025/12/warning-letter-or-ten-businesses-comply-ftcs-consumer-review-rule">FTC now enforces penalties</a> of up to $53,088 per violation for businesses caught buying or fabricating reviews.</p>
<p><strong>How do online reviews affect local SEO rankings?</strong></p>
<p>Review signals (volume, velocity, diversity, and response rate) account for roughly 16% of <a href="/blog/local-seo-ranking-factors/">local SEO ranking factors</a> according to Whitespark. Google weighs review quantity, recency, and sentiment when ranking businesses in the local pack and Google Maps.</p>
